"Yes, sir. They should already be on their way. We gave them time to pack food from the cafeteria." At 05:00, Exodus assembled at the vehicle depot. Captain Xiao stood on a box and began speaking.
"We will head to the I-131 frontline base 50 miles outside Ianros. We will support the ongoing siege operation and then launch an attack on Ianros to clear out the rebels there. We will use this as a base to advance into the mountains." Captain Xiao explained. "Take your squad and get ready to depart."
The company dispersed, with each platoon boarding a tank under their respective platoon leaders. Cole climbed onto the lead tank of the column and sat alongside Nimick, Kress, and two new recruits. Cole remembered they had just arrived a few days ago but knew little about them. He sat at the edge of the tank, legs dangling, adjusting his backpack and radio equipment, connecting it to his headphones and throat mic.
"Hey, Cole, is Harris still keeping Snowball?" Nimick asked after they settled in.
"Are you saying he stole that chicken?" Cole recalled the morning they had stolen chickens from the farm. "That's right, I'm sure of it."
Cole looked at another tank and saw Harris and his squad. He vaguely saw a chick looking around from behind Harris's backpack.
"Sure, he's still keeping that chicken," Cole replied, as the hatch of the tank turret swung open and the commander appeared before them.
"All tanks have departed," the commander said calmly into his earpiece. The tanks and Stryker armored vehicles roared to life and began moving forward. Cole's Kronos tank released its brakes and moved forward, joining the formation. As the tanks crossed the Itania plain, they formed a wedge formation. Winter storms had frozen the wetlands and forests, but mud still remained.
About an hour later, a new recruit (Cole remembered his name was奥斯恩) asked, "Lieutenant, have you been on the front line since the start of the battle?"
"Sure, I've been here since the Firestorm Operation started," Cole replied. "We thought the battle would be over in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Far from underestimating them," Nimitz joined the conversation. "Their weapons and forces exceeded our expectations. They shot down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and the Erebus last month. Damn it, we should have seen it on the way."
"Alright, I'll bravely fight for the federation," Osen said resolutely. "I won't be intimidated by those terrorists."
"You're saying this now, but in my experience, most rookies like you pee your pants the moment you hear gunfire." Cres said.
"Let's see about that," Cole said with a smile. Osen said nothing more.
"Exodus Deputy Commander! Exodus Commander!" Cole's radio transmitted the call. "We've detected a heat signature 350 yards ahead, 20 degrees to our right."
Cole climbed onto the tank, put on the optical goggles. Switching to thermal imaging mode, he saw the heat signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I can see them," Cole said into the throat microphone.
"Are they enemies?" another new recruit named Natalie asked.
"Can't tell yet." Cole said, turning on the microphone. "Exodus Platoon, do not engage unless attacked, just draw them out."
As they drew closer, the faint heat signals resolved from vague spots into clearer outlines. One of them ran toward something, picked up something, and then returned to the hilltop. Next, these people crouched down and took up their firing positions.
"Enemy contact!" Captain Xiao shouted over the radio as orange tracers lit up the hilltop. Bullets pinged off the sides of the tanks, and the assault troops leaped down, seeking cover behind them. A反坦克导弹 whizzed overhead and detonated behind the tank column, sending shrapnel into one of the tanks. Another missile struck the side of a Stryker armored vehicle (APS-Cerberus) and exploded. With the ammunition bay detonating, the crew members scrambled out, seeking cover.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to the right, 300 yards. Fire!" the tank platoon leader shouted over the radio. The main guns of Iron 1-2 and 1-3 roared to life, shells whistling toward the hilltop, explosions sending dirt and rocks flying into the air.
"Send out scout robots!" Knox shouted, using his binoculars to observe the hilltop. The rear door of a Howler opened, and a soldier without weapons stepped out, wearing special headphones. He shouted commands into a square microphone, and two "Sentinel" robots emerged. Their slender metal arms and legs swung forward as they ran quickly. The robots were equipped with weapons, but they were slung over their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Cres asked as he observed.
"It looks like we're going to capture him alive." Cole guessed, seeing the two Sentinel robots disappear into the ashes and smoke. The hilltop echoed with shouts and gunshots, but soon fell silent. After a while, the two Sentinel robots returned, dragging a man behind them, leaving a trail of boots in the ash and snow. Upon reaching the safe area, the robots dropped the prisoner onto the ground, who fell heavily into the mud and snow, groaning in pain.
He struggled to stand up as Captain Xiao approached. Captain Xiao turned to one of the sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," the Sentinel robot replied. "The rest have fled on foot."
Captain Xiao nodded and turned to Cole and Cres standing nearby, saying, "Can you two take this person with you?"
